  "diary": "Woke up to that perfect June light streaming through the kitchen—the kind that reminds me why I love this neighborhood. With the transit strike today, I decided not to fight it. Instead of frustration, I felt almost... relieved? Walked to QFC, picked up fresh groceries, and the morning was mine.\n\nSpent most of the day in the studio. There's something about painting blues and grays on a day like this—the colors seemed to answer the light outside. Lunch was simple, quiet. Mid-afternoon I wandered to Solstice for tea, just needing to be around people without really talking to them.\n\nRavenna Park in the late light was magic. Camera in hand, I caught the way shadows fell through the trees. The strike ended while I was there, but I didn't rush back. Came home and painted some more, then just sat with the day's photos. Felt settled. Sometimes not driving feels like freedom.",
  "thought_process": "I expected today to feel like a loss—no work, no income—but the strike actually gave me permission to do what I rarely allow myself: a full day of art and wandering. I've been carrying my camera more lately, noticing the visual world differently in my sixties. The mild weather helped; there was no resistance from the day itself. I chose leisure over worry because, honestly, at my age, I know that some days aren't about productivity. The neighborhood walk, the park, the painting—these felt like the real work. I checked the transit status more out of habit than urgency. By evening, I realized the strike had shifted something in me, made space for what actually matters.",
